value.value: A thin, transparent sheet made of regenerated cellulose.

definition.value: Cellophane is used for food packaging.

value.value: Synthetic plastic which is composed of a glossy, moistureproof membrane made of rubber hydrochloride.
A polyester film made from stretched polyethylene terephthalate (PET).
A solid environmental material that is hard, brittle, heat-resistant and corrosion-resistant, made by shaping and then firing a nonmetallic mineral at a high temperature.
A stable dispersion (emulsion) of polymer microparticles in an aqueous medium.

definition.value: Latex is made by some plants, but synthetic latexes can be manufactured as well.

value.value: A liquid water which has no current or flow and is susceptible to contamination by pathogens or pathogenic vectors.

definition.value: Dust which is 1) generated when wood is processed and 2) composed primarily of cellulose, polyoses, and lignin.

Wood dust is typically generated through processes where wood is chipped, sawed, turned, drilled or sanded. The chemical composition of wood dust depends on the species of tree. Wood dust is not typically produced for specific uses. However, it is used commercially for wood composts. The primary routes of potential human exposure to wood dust are inhalation and dermal contact. It is known to be a human carcinogen.

value.value: A liquid fuel used in diesel engines, whose fuel ignition takes place, without any spark, as a result of compression of the inlet air mixture and then injection of fuel.
A clear petroleum-derived flammable liquid which is used as fuel in most spark-ignited internal combustion engines.

definition.value: Gasoline consists mostly of organic compounds obtained by the fractional distillation of petroleum, enhanced with a variety of additives.
A gas which results from the incomplete or complete combustion of diesel fuel.

value.value: A gas which results from the complete or incomplete combustion of gasoline fuel.

definition.value: A polysaccharide that functions as an emulsifier, stabilizer, and thickener in mixtures.
A naturally occurring plant-based gum, which functions as a viscous, odorless, tasteless, water-soluble mixture of polysaccharides that absorbs water to become a gel/paste.
Tragacanth has many uses, including as an emulsifier, thickener, stabilizer, and texturant additive for foods, pharmaceuticals, and art materials.

value.value: A solid or highly viscous plant or synthetic based substance that is typically convertible into polymers.
A resin secreted by the female lac bug, which is dissolved in alcohol to be used as a brush-on colorant, food glaze, and wood finish.
A paint product which adheres to surfaces and forms a binding layer, preparing it to receive paint.
A slow-drying paint that consists of particles of pigment suspended in a drying oil, commonly linseed oil.
A water soluble, fast-drying paint made of pigment suspended in acrylic polymer emulsion.
A paint that exhibits luminescence, giving off visible light through fluorescence, phosphorescence, or radioluminescence.
Dust which is composed of minerals and trace elements, generated by  finely crushed rock.

definition.value: Rock dust is widely used in mining to prevent coal dust explosions, or in agriculture for organic farming uses.

value.value: Any material containing unstable atoms that emit ionizing radiation as it decays.
An environmental material which is primarily composed of cyanoacrolate.

definition.value: Cyanoacrylates have industrial, medical, and household uses. A strong fast-acting adhesive which is an ester of cyanoacrylic acid.
An environmental material which is composed of elastic polymers mixed in a solvent.
Solvents typically used include acetone, hexane, heptane or toluene.
An environmental material which is 1) composed primarily of methyl cellulose and water, and 2) formulated to fix wallpaper to walls.
An environmental material which is 1) manufactured and 2) primarily composed of hydrogen peroxide and ammonia, and 3) when applied to hair, can alter the natural hair pigments for 6-8 weeks.
A colorant fluid which is 1) manufactured and 2) composed of alcohol, titanium dioxide, and propylene glycol.
A colorant fluid which is 1) manufactured and 2) composed of copper phthalocyanine, iron oxides, water, and biopolymers.
A colorant fluid which is 1) manufactured and 2) primarily composed of soybean oil, as well as pigment, resin, and wax.
A colorant fluid which is 1) manufactured, 2) primarily composed of water, as well as glycol, and dye, and 3) intended for use in inkjet printers.
An environmental material which is composed primarily of gases and particles produced by the combustion of petroleum fuels.
A liquid environmental material which 1) contains at least one substance which can act as a chemical colorant.

value.value: Waste which contains toxic components (e.g., heavy metals or radiation) which can cause harm to organisms and/or the environment.
A water ice crystal which is constituted by water molecules aligned in a hexagonal array.
Sediment which contains some chemical contaminant.
Liquid water which is a participant in a water cooling process.
Cooling water is commonly used for cooling automobile internal combustion engines and power stations.
A waste material which is primarily composed of uneaten food and removed from the food supply chain.
The causes of food waste or loss are numerous and can occur during production, processing, distribution, retail and consumption.
A fluid environmental material which is contained in geologic formations naturally.
Liquid water which occurs naturally within the pores of rocks and sediments.

An environmental material which consists of either loose sands or partially consolidated sandstone, containing a naturally occurring mixture of sand, clay, and water, soaked with a dense and extremely viscous form of petroleum.
Rock which is derived from bedrock through chemical weathering
An environmental material which is composed of insoluble solid particles suspended in a liquid.
Soil which has properties that restrict a pathogen's ability to establish itself, persist, or cause disease that results in long-term harm.

definition.value: The pathogenicity that is suppressed is typically directed towards plants, especially crops. Soils are typically classified as pathogen-suppressive if a pathogen 1) cannot establish itself or persist, 2) is able to establish itself, but causes little or no damage, or 3) is able to establishe itself, but only causes disease that does not result in long-term harm.

value.value: Liquid water which is either part of or was removed from a marine lake.
A sedimentary rock which is made of carbonate mud whose formation is mediated by microbes in the benthic zone.
Water which comes from a spring.
Fresh water which is harvested from cloud.
Fluid environmental material which is present in the continental crust and dictates the nature and extent of crustal deformation.

definition.value: The presence or absence of fluids exerts a fundamental control on rheology.

value.value: An organic material which is derived from lichen mats.

definition.value: Water which is part of a lake.

value.value: Organic material in soil, which consists of plant and animal residues at various stages of decomposition, cells and tissues of soil organisms, and substances synthesized by soil organisms.
